segments.text: So planning 621 and planning 623 were courses that were created to try to address the interest that was emerging on campus by some students who wanted to work in developing countries.
And in time, as I offered them more and more, there seemed to be more interest for the planning 623 course because it was a broader course.
It covered not only Latin America, but also the other parts of the developing world and the third world.
And I then began to teach that one more often, 623.
And the Latin 621 was just specialized in Latin America less often, because I was able to attract all types.
And it really made for a more interesting class.
And that's being taught to this day.
So let's take a look at the structure of the university, the college, and the department when you return from Cali.
Well, we had, of course, a program chairman, which I interpret to be a department, since we were a department at the time, as I recall, a department of the college.
Yes, the department existed within the college.
But I'm trying to remember when we became accredited, but I think we were accredited in 1968 by the AIP.
So that means that veteran would have been in existence for three years is one of the requirements, have reduced a certain number of minimum number of graduates.
Right.
Was an autonomous unit within the college, meaning a department.
Had control of our own budget.
We meant control of its budget and the department had, could in fact assign, was assigned a department operating expense in faculty positions.
And so that all those criteria were required by AIP at the time.
and had been met in there because we were accredited, if I recall, in 1968 was the first year we became accredited.
And I believe it was the first program in the state of Texas to receive such a recognition.
So we had the departmental format and small faculty, to be sure, a growing department.
It was a young, growing department struggling to establish itself and develop a constituency, of course, and build up the course offerings.
Well, how was it structured?
Who was leading who?
How did we report to the university structure?
Well, of course, the department head reported to the dean.
The department head was Joe McGraw.
Joseph McGraw, Joe McGraw.
Then he reported, of course, to Ed Romanek, who was the dean at the time.
But it was my understanding that our academic programs
was not lodged in the College of Architecture.
It was in the College of Engineering.
And our administrative dean was the architecture dean.
And so that all of our faculty salaries were those of the College of Engineering.
And then when that was changed, because when I was hired, I had to interview with Dean Benson of engineering, not Ramanek.
I see.
OK, yeah.
I don't remember that experience myself, because I interviewed with Ed Romnick, yes, and I didn't interview with Dean Benson.
I remember that you mentioned that initially when the program was first recommended,

It was supposed to, because the College of Architecture, when it was the School of Architecture, was under the Dean of Engineering, was part of the School of Engineering, or the College of Engineering.
But a school within the college.
A school within the college.
Then they changed it from a school and made it a full-fledged college.
And of course, that wasn't existed by the time I came back.
Do you know when that occurred?
Oh, gee, it must have been 65, somewhere in there, if I remember correctly.
About the time that Joe McGraw got back here?
Yeah, it may have been 64, perhaps, and a little bit before he came.
And see, Joe and Ed had actually proposed a planning program way back, long before this, you know.
I would say back in 1960, something like that, or 59, 58, somewhere.
When Joe was originally teaching architecture.
Yeah, right.
But he had gone through Harvard and city planning and, of course, had the planning background experience and began to teach planning-related subjects within the school.
programs, and Ed had expressed an interest in, yes, setting up a funding emphasis and a funding program.

So they had submitted those ideas way back, and I guess those were used then to create, once the College was created of architecture, College of Architecture and Environmental Design was created, then they resubmitted the request for establishing a department, and this was a new college establishing departments, and the idea was accepted.
And I suppose because they'd been part of the engineering college, then they felt that they needed this coordination with engineering in making this transition and establishing the program jointly.
But that doesn't, then when did we report to the interdisciplinary committee that Van Riper from political science and the other faculty members, Virgil Stover from civil engineering,
And what's his name from Parks and Recreation?
Like the clear gun?
Clear gun.
Well, as I recall, that was a... What's his name from geography?
Sonnenfeld.

Okay, well, that was a committee that I guess existed before I came, and as I understood it, that was a committee that the department had us to work with and coordinate with, although... And report to.
I suppose, yeah.
Periodically.
Periodically.
That's part of a coordinated effort.
But I don't remember any gatherings as such, you know, that we had with them.
I assume that the department head was communicating with them.
That's an administrative function more than anything else.
But we were running the funding program.
We felt that we were the trained people in the field, and we knew what the field needed and what the field required.
And we had a 48 hour recognized program, 48 credit hour recognized program, of which about 25% were outside of the department.
And I can tell you,
model program because most of the curriculums did not require that of other students.
But we were committed to the interdisciplinary philosophy of planning.
I was conversing with the concept that was developed in Chicago at the University of Chicago back in the 50s when our friend from California
Well, one of the initiators of the interdisciplinary planning concept, and he used the University of Chicago as his base to try to test it.
And I believe it lasted three or four years there, and then they did away with the program.
As a matter of fact, I applied there the year that the program collapsed.
He's now the dean at UCLA.
Oh, okay.
Well, who recently died.
Yes, yes.
Very well known, of course, in the field throughout the world, too.
Okay.
Not Voorhees.
No.
G.U.S.
Oh, thank you.
Yeah.
Okay.

So we were committed to the interdisciplinary approach to planning, so students would be aware of the economic and social implications of the physical needs of the field, administrative aspects, dealing with city government and how planning could be implemented, and, of course, the capital improvements aspects of it.
And this broadness required, we felt, exposure to other fields as well.
So they took courses in economics and sociology, political science.
And of course, we modeled this curriculum.
Each student was a specially designed curriculum that met the core requirements first.

And then beyond that, then we would specialize the curriculum to a particular student's interests, maybe more into the physical design or more into administrative, political aspects, government aspects, or perhaps social aspects.

It gave the program an interesting, how would you say, it was appealing to many students because when they read our catalogs, they felt they could model a curriculum to their interest, which is very different from other schools where they had to model it after the faculty's interest and with very little leeway.
Well, it's a broad enough field that just about anyone can find their own niche in it.
Exactly, exactly.
And that was the point we were trying to make, that there was just about nothing that planning didn't touch in giving a community life, you know.

And that what we were trying to say was that planning should be part of, on the one hand, the policy-making part, which was to formulate with the mayor and the council and the planning commissioners long-range planning policy for a community.
But it also could be very technical.
If you wanted to get down to the transportation end of it, to the housing end of it, you could get into the technical areas and be more of a technical type.
OK. Well, so we had the university operating, I think, department operating under this umbrella interdisciplinary committee.
And Joe McGraw was the department head.
Right.
Then what was the next change in the administration?

Well, I guess because of the unique nature of the program and the fact that we were sort of a maverick operation, really we were a maverick department as the department went on this campus, we dealt with sensitive issues that were politically based issues.
And as we talked about earlier about the political turmoil in the country, I guess we were sometimes looked at with strange
It's a strange operation.
We tend to sometimes ruffle feathers to put it in a party way.
Well, I think planning dealt with government and with political issues.
Yes.
So that was new for the university administration.
Here, yes.
Especially at A&M, yeah.
Yeah, to handle that kind of a thing.
Exactly, exactly.
And then the environmental issues became a powerful tool and that affected our campus as well.
And we would oftentimes be outspoken about certain issues and would bring attention to ourselves.
And our students would maybe raise questions in classrooms oftentimes.
And we would get feedback from other faculty that our students would raise, in fact, critical issues that other students from other careers would not raise, you know.
And they did tend to create turmoil in the positive sense in terms of intellectual searching.
So anyway, that, of course, and I guess there were some problems of administration that surfaced, allocation of funds or the use of funds or the reporting procedures.
Somehow that was brought up or something to that effect happened.
And so all of a sudden we were in a turmoil in terms of how we related to who and what and administration.
Our very existence was questioned at one time.
And in fact, I saw a memorandum was handed to me one time showing some wording to the effect that they might abolish the department.
So I became very concerned about this because I had made, you know, made an effort to come back to A&M to build an interesting, a good and solid program at A&M.
And I felt we had a good faculty, a very well-educated and experienced faculty.
And I felt we had a good program, a good format.
And I felt it was just misunderstood, and therefore,
People were maybe, you know, perhaps being a little too critical about certain things and therefore were putting the whole program in jeopardy.

So essentially what happened was that we were put under basically the Dean of Engineering and the reporting and everything else was so strict, you know, that Professor McGraw decided he didn't want to fall under that umbrella or didn't feel that it was appropriate for him to be a department head and not have the autonomy that was required.
So he decided to resign the position.
So we were left there with no department head for a while, and the dean of the college was then asked to oversee the department in its interim period.
That was Romany.
Yes.
He was dean at the time, and so he was asked to become the overseer of the operation.
But of course, he was an architect and mostly concerned with the College of Architecture, not only with architecture, but the other departments.
What year was that?
Gee, I'm trying to remember.
It was probably about 1970.
One or two?
Sixty-nine, maybe?
No, no, no.
Oh, I'm sorry, 70.
I think maybe in the fall of 70 or spring of 70, you know.
Because I had just come, I think I had just come back from Colombia, you know, that would have been early 70.
Somewhere in there.
Yeah.
And so, of course, the faculty wanted to keep the program going.
And we felt strongly about it.
And we had students.
And we were a growing department.
So we, of course, accepted this sort of overview committee under the dean of engineering.
And so then Dean Romanek asked me if, well, began to ask me if I could look into the secretaries, see if they needed any help or had any questions and so forth.
So it was sort of a de facto I became like a department head.
by overseeing their work and answering this or filling out forms and all that.
So then after a semester of that, Dean Romanek then recommended me to the administration as interim head of the department until, you know, some decision could be made.
So they accepted that.
So I was interim department head and worked in that position, I believe, for about a year, maybe less.
And then he elevated the recommendation to full, you know,
department head and they accepted it and I served as the department head position until I left to go to Nicaragua.

I was asked by AID if I would go to Nicaragua to work on the reconstruction of Managua and I would be principal international advisor to the vice minister of urban planning and I felt that by then the department had stabilized and that we were
And we were back in charge again.
In other words, the dean of engineering had seen that we were, in fact, we were following our own policies of 25% coursework outside of the department.
And the students were, you know, those standards were being met and everything else.
And, in fact, we were under scrutiny by this committee for a year, a whole year.
We met over at the graduate college under dean, who was dean of the graduate college at the time.
Yeah, we'll remember anyway here in a moment.
And he brought the committee together.
It was an internship committee from around the campus.
Everybody except, there was nobody from the college.
They were all outside of the college.
And we would, I met all their answers and requirements, and we reviewed curriculums.
We reviewed department programs, and we looked at student degree programs at random.
And they asked, could we look in and see if there's an effect happening?
Because you say here that they require, that you require 25% outside the department.
And so I said, yes, go ahead.
I mean, I had to give the clearance.
They wouldn't have looked at the files without my approval.
But I went ahead and said, yes, go ahead.
So they pulled out at random files from the graduate college records.
And they, in fact, were able to confirm that not only did we meet the 25%, all the time we exceeded it.
So that we were, in other words, being consistent in our policies and in their implementation.
And the other important thing was that we were meeting the recognition criteria of the AIP at the time.
Excuse me a minute.
To the transcriber, you can go back and fill in the name of the graduate college dean.
Was Dean George W. Kunze?
Yes, exactly.
K-U-N-Z-E. K-U-N-Z-E, very much so.
And so Dean Kunze was very fair in the whole procedure.
He oversaw the whole procedure.
And the committee members, they were from political science, Ben Riper, Paul Ben Riper.
I believe it was Joe Sonnenfeld from geography and so forth.
I mean, they were all very qualified people and very respected faculty on the campus.
And sympathetic to the idea.
Yeah.
Oh, yes.
Very much so.
And they were very interested in the program.
They wanted the program to succeed.
And they were convinced and they were satisfied that the program was being run properly.
And so then, at that point, they released us from this overseer.
We were then became a full-fledged department, autonomous department at that point.
And the other important thing was that we had to meet the AIP requirements, and they could only be met by us, you see.
That was the important thing.
That's why I'm also in favor of standards for recognition, and because... Well, Chewy, when you left for Nicaragua, who then became department head?
Okay, the request came in the fall, I believe it was fall of 74, and I asked Dean Reed at the time if he thought it would be okay.
for me to accept this appointment.
And he said, well, yes, let us begin.
So Romanek had been replaced by Ray Reed?
Oh, yes, yes, that's right.
Ray Reed had come on board, I guess, two or three years before that.
From the University of Iowa.
Yes, exactly.
He became the dean of the college, exactly.
I forget about that.
So, you know, I checked with him, and he said, yes, if
It's an important program.
It would be a credit to the college and to the department, to the university.
We definitely would be interested in you doing it.
And so all I'm interested in is that you can find a way to transition and then have someone else come on board.
It would be in the spring of 75. Who did that?
And as I recall, Professor Stover, I believe, Dr. Virgil Stover from civil engineering, who had a joint appointment with planning.
was asked then to serve as interim department head.
He served for one semester.
I believe so, because then, well, let's see, was there somebody else then?
He served for one semester and one summer, I believe it was.
And I might add personally that Stober's administration was quite a surprise to everybody because he turned
He was extremely liberal in his administration, and he was very concerned with any individual's problems and trying to solve them.
And although mistakes were made, they were honest mistakes, and he moved very quickly to correct them.
So that as an interim department head, in my judgment, he was excellent.
That's good.
I didn't experience that because I was abroad.
Either way.
But I had a, I'm telling you, for me it was a grim experience as a department head because my job was to protect the department from extinction.
And I felt that I had done that job and I had no, ever had any aspirations to be a department head in the first place.
But I felt that we needed to protect the department and that happened.
And so when this opportunity developed in Manawa, which is an interesting assignment,
I said, I would like to try it, you know.
Well, why was the department so near to being abolished by the administration?

Well, again, I think it was this misunderstanding about what we were about, and they just weren't quite ready at the time to accept the fact that departments could get involved with politically-based issues and really get out there and do things.
You know, we were involved in the Model Cities program.
That was something that Joe McGraw got us into way back, and

I think it occurred a little bit before I came to the department, when we first got involved with it, and we would send out interns out to the communities, and they would deal with very, really serious social and economic problems, with deteriorated neighborhoods that were, you know, up in arms, because how come we don't have water and sewer, and, you know, no funds to repair our homes, so the model cities program was a very important internship, part of our internship program, and we made that
Eventually that became a model, and we used that.
I can see that that would be upsetting to the administration that was not used to having such activist roles.
Exactly.

And sometimes I think they also received, on occasion, phone calls, you see, because our students were making some pretty aggressive recommendations to some of these communities, and we ourselves as faculty oftentimes would make an impression or make a suggestion that might not set well.
And though there were also some irregularities in...
the funding and administration of resources?
Yeah, there was some accounting procedures that were not followed.
And of course, that is not necessarily, I don't think there were any legalities in terms of, you know, but more in terms of procedures that have to be followed or required by the state.
And I think that eventually the administration
felt that they couldn't handle that anymore because it would reflect eventually badly on upper-level administrators who had to oversee this.
As I recall, there was a substantial amount of ill will generated at that time.
Yes.
Oh yeah, I had to overcome all of that.
It was really painful, I'm telling you.
So that, yeah, that was sort of in your lap.
Oh yes, I had to take all that and run with it, you know, and I had to actually work towards
de-siphoning all that, or how do you say it, or defusing, rather, that negative animosity that had been built up.
A lot of it, I think, just totally unwarranted, but it was just the politics of the time.
A lot of conservatives that were on the faculty since then have changed, you know, but to some extent, much more so.
And you're talking about the upper administration, not the faculty.
No, not the faculty.

Although, of course, some faculty in other departments would also be overreacting to what some of the things we were doing, where they inevitably, I'm sure, go up and talk against us, perhaps at meetings elsewhere if they had the opportunity.
Typical campus politics.
Yeah, very much so.

See, we were trying to get into the real world, and we were trying to put ourselves not only exposed to theory, but to the application of theory, because that's where it really means something, to get out there and really try something and to test ideas.
In spite of our location in College Station.
That was one of the great things about the Model Cities program and putting our internships out there.
Yeah, that was a good program that was brought to the department by Joe and his efforts.
John Shanahan, in fact, was also very instrumental in that program.
He helped Joe in getting that program established.
initially worked on it, and I then got involved with it myself in helping place students.
And later on, of course, I had to supervise the placement of students as part of the department responsibilities.
But interestingly enough, we always had good feedback from the students' work.
Okay, so as the department became stabilized, we had shown the administration we were a responsible faculty, we had the qualifications, and we could run a good program, a recognized program.
I felt good.
I mean, so we had stabilized the program and were being finally given back the reins to the department.

And at the time, this was in the fall of 74, I got a request from a USAID if I wanted to go to Central America, to Manawa, Nicaragua, to help with the reconstruction of Manawa, which had been damaged by an earthquake.
And I had the opportunity to work in South America.
I wanted to do more of that.
I thought it was good for us as a department and a university to be involved.
Central America and the Latin American region.
And it was a unique experience, actually.
It was a unique project to work in the reconstruction of a major capital city.
So I was, AID said, if you want to go during the
Thanksgiving holidays and look around, talk to the people over there, visit with them, they can interview with you and you can see if you like the situation.
You might make a decision over the holidays and before Christmas and then we'll know if we can depend on you and you can get your clearance from the university.
This was 1974.
In 74, right.
This would be in October of 74, November, I'm sorry, Thanksgiving holidays of 74.
So I did that and I went and visited and came back and I was impressed by the work that was being done and the scale and the magnitude of the project.
It was
a UN team working there, and then the AAD team.
It was about a total of about 50 or 60 professionals that I would be overseeing, helping the Vice Minister of Riverland oversee the reconstruction program, which was vetted at over $70 million.
So I came back and I talked to Ray Reed, of course, the dean at the time, and I asked Ray if he thought it would be okay for me to accept this assignment.
I was interested in the assignment if there was no problem with him.

And he said, no, it's no problem, as long as I can have some time to transition, meaning that I would have to stay probably at least a month into the next semester to help somebody take over the department, or help him actually manage the department meanwhile until he could find someone.
And so we agreed to that, and so I went ahead and made my commitments to AAD and got everything arranged.
And I was able to leave in early 75 to go to Manawa and work on the project.
And I understand that later,
Dr. Virgil Stover was then asked to serve as interim department head at the time to run the program in the fall of, sorry, in the spring of 1975.
And then, of course, I was gone for a year.
The contract was for one year.
And during that time, I guess, as you remember earlier, Virgil served, I guess, through the summer of 75.
And Dean Reed had asked me if he wanted me to hold the position open for me.
But I could be, I could come back to department head.
And I felt that it was not appropriate.
I thought it would be best to have a permanent person assigned to the department head position.
I didn't think it was good to have interim department heads.
It would just not help us with our marketing the program.
And so then a search was begun.
I believe Dr. Rosler was then hired by the University Service Permanent Department Head.
While I was in Managua, this all has occurred.
I managed then later on to, of course, be in touch with Dr. Roesler through communications through telephone and mail.
And what actually happened, I was asked to stay another year in Manawa.
And I got an extension.
The university approved the extension.
And so I stayed there for two years.
In fact, we stayed in Manawa for two years.
Very interesting assignment working, helping rebuild the major capital city that was damaged very heavily by an earthquake in 73.
the immediate emergency reconstruction had taken place, basically clearing the roads and cordoning off a lot of the downtown area because 90% of the downtown had been damaged and destroyed.

And so our job was to come up with new plans and what was called an immediate action reconstruction program, which is to rebuild the city, and it would cost over $70 million to do that, to just get it to a certain level of operation and rebuild the infrastructure, the streets, new land uses, and so forth.
And, but because of the danger of the, there were four major faults that went to downtown and the lack of understanding of what those faults might do in the future.
They had hired a firm from California to do some engineering work and geology work.
And they did that and they identified the faults and, and so then we were able to then make some recommendations based on the new information.
So it was an interesting new land use planning being based on
faults and the types of soils and what could be, what could not be put on those areas.
Okay, so then we, the teams were working together, the AID team and the UN-led team.
The UN-led team was basically working on long-range planning, and the AID team was working on in the direction of construction programming and planning.
And so the work had
was complex enough and it required so much effort to put together that I would have to stay another year.
So I stayed another year to finish the programming of this project.
And I was able to come back right before things got very messy in Nicaragua when the Sandinista movement became to surface.
And I felt that it was time for us to get back anyway.
I wanted to get back to the campus and continue my association with the department program.
And so we got back in the early... Of course, you were there with your family.
Yes, right.
My family was there with me.
My kids grew up eating mangoes and learning Spanish in Nicaragua, the older ones, of course.
And so, yeah, we came back in early 77.
We got back to the campus.
And, of course, by then, we had a new department head.
Dr. Rose had been department head, I guess, by then for about a year and a quarter, perhaps, you know.
and had been instrumental in giving new direction to the department with his background and experience.
And I guess had gotten a couple of faculty positions approved.
And I believe Dr. Pugh was at the time had already by then had joined the faculty.
And we had had another young fellow, I can't recall his name, was also in the faculty in mathematical type.
I was supposed to be working with statistics and quantification techniques.
And then a young lady.
Who went to Brooklyn College?
Sharon, I think.
Sharon.
Sharon, I believe, was her.
In health planning.
Yeah, health planning was her area of interest.
And she worked with Don Sweeney.
And Don Sweeney, at the time, also, I guess, had joined our faculty.
I don't remember if it was on the faculty or not.
I think he was working on the health emphasis by then.
Although he was associate dean, I believe, too.

And I believe had functioned at one time anyway as associate dean and was now also on our faculty working on the health program, health emphasis program, which was a growing and emerging area of interest.
And so I came back, of course.
Dr. Rosa wanted me to help with the area of physical planning and emphasis towards Latin American region.

He felt that my background in the region would be a strength and also to help with students that we had, a lot of students from the Central American and South American area and some from Mexico that were interested in our program and help counsel those students.
So I was sort of assigned that kind of an area of emphasis and concentrated on physical planning and
an emphasis towards the Latin American region.

We had a program, if you recall, we worked with, when I had been working in Costa Rica earlier, this is what our department had, we developed a program to work with public officials in Costa Rica to help establish planning in Costa Rica, local planning in Costa Rica.
And we worked with a gentleman named Armando Rouse.
His first name is A-R-M-A-N-D-O.
Second name, last name is A-R-A-U-Z.
And he was the director of an interesting institute, which was developed to support community development.
And so with him, who had some planning experience, we developed the first planning efforts in Costa Rica.
And his institute then transferred all that to the National Planning Office.
When did all this happen?
Well, that was 70, let's see, it was 73, somewhere in there, 74.
You didn't mention Costa Rica before.
No, I had forgotten about that.
In fact, Clark Davis and I worked on that, and it was an oversight on my part.
When I was department head, Claude and I developed this program.
I had met some... That was before you went to South America at all, wasn't it?
Well, no, it was after because... After which?
After Colombia, because... After Colombia.
One of the AID officers that I got to know when I was working in Colombia was transferred to Costa Rica and was interested in my helping him with some projects he was doing, he was working on.
And when we had worked in Cali, in Colombia,
He knew my work and was interested in what I had done.
So he asked me if I would go and do some consulting.
So I went.
And I spent some time.
And so then he introduced me to this gentleman from this other institution, Community Development Institute.
And then he asked me, well, I explained that we had a program here at A&M.
We had been working with people from South Texas, people in local government.
I had developed a program that was funded under the National Endowment for the Arts.
for public officials, and Claude and I had worked on that.

And we put it together, and we would bring public officials to A&M for six weeks out of the year, one week at a time, and we exposed them to a series of lectures on planning and design and architecture and writing, oral presentations and so forth.

The techniques that a manager in a small office in a small community with not too much background in any professional area, especially planning, might be better prepared to deal with consultants whenever they were asking for work.
And so the NEA thought it was an interesting project, and they funded it.
So we did that project.
I remember I gave one lecture on California planning.
Right.
All the faculty somehow were involved in giving lectures or presentations or showing this or showing that.
And if you recall, we did the same to the chapter.
We had some presentations in Corpus Christi and other cities, and we did similar programs for public officials.
So I explained this program to the people in Costa Rica, and they liked it.
They said, why don't you do it for us?
You should do it for us, they said.
I said, well, I guess we could, you know, if there's enough funding to support it.
So then they said they were interested in doing that.
And so then I came back, and a few months later, a few weeks later, they sent this check for $10,000 for us to do.
And they sent the check in my name, mind you, you know.
And so I said, what am I going to do with this?
I told them it had to be to the university.
So I ran to the fiscal office and had it cashed and deposited immediately to the departmental accounts, you know.
And then we went to see the university administration about it.
these clearances that we needed to do this because they really did it with no warning.
We thought we were going to go into some negotiation period, but they just sent the money and said, do it.
So we were thrust into this thing.
So we did it, and that was for three years, by the way.
It was extended twice after that.
And the last year, I think the last two visits were handled by Claude and then Dr. Roosevelt while I was gone because we started the program.
It must have been in 73, 74, somewhere in there.
And then they were, in 75 and 76, I was already in Manawa, you know.
